397
00:22:45.360 --> 00:22:49.040
Thank you. And so I'm going to talk about muscle-invasive bladder

398
00:22:49.120 --> 00:22:51.160
cancer. Here are my disclosures.

399
00:22:53.220 --> 00:22:57.020
And I suspect there's some differences in familiarity with bladder

400
00:22:57.060 --> 00:23:00.740
cancer among those in the audience, so I'm going to start from the

401
00:23:00.780 --> 00:23:04.380
basics here and present a patient vignette, which I think

402
00:23:04.400 --> 00:23:07.160
highlights some of the key points about muscle-invasive bladder cancer.

403
00:23:07.770 --> 00:23:11.260
So our patient's an 80-year-old man, and he presents with gross

404
00:23:11.300 --> 00:23:13.980
hematuria, that's blood in his urine, with no pain.

405
00:23:14.040 --> 00:23:17.460
He presents to his primary care doctor, and his primary care

406
00:23:17.500 --> 00:23:21.320
doctor astutely recognizes that blood in the urine in

407
00:23:21.380 --> 00:23:23.780
an older patient is cancer until proven

408
00:23:23.840 --> 00:23:27.820
otherwise. So he orders a CAT scan, and you can see the CAT scan.

409
00:23:27.860 --> 00:23:30.260
I don't know if I can show-- Does my arrow show up? Yeah.

410
00:23:30.740 --> 00:23:32.800
So you can see that there's bladder wall thickening.

411
00:23:32.860 --> 00:23:35.020
This is suspicious for a bladder tumor.

412
00:23:35.340 --> 00:23:39.200
So he's referred to a urologist, and the urologist places

413
00:23:39.240 --> 00:23:43.140
a fiber optic scope into the bladder in the office,

414
00:23:43.180 --> 00:23:46.960
a cystoscope, and is able to visualize the inner lining of the

415
00:23:46.980 --> 00:23:50.900
bladder, sees a tumor there, and then schedules the patient to go

416
00:23:50.980 --> 00:23:54.500
to the operating room for a rigid scope through which

417
00:23:54.560 --> 00:23:57.800
instruments can be placed. And you can see the scope here.

418
00:23:57.920 --> 00:24:01.740
You can see a bladder tumor, and you see the resection loop here.

419
00:24:02.100 --> 00:24:04.760
And this procedure is called a TURBT

420
00:24:05.740 --> 00:24:08.620
or transurethral resection of bladder tumor.

421
00:24:08.700 --> 00:24:12.660
This procedure is sometimes a therapeutic procedure, but it's always a

422
00:24:12.680 --> 00:24:16.380
diagnostic procedure. And this helps us define the

423
00:24:16.440 --> 00:24:19.880
clinical stage of the disease, and you can see we just heard from Dr.

424
00:24:20.080 --> 00:24:23.820
Abbosh about non-muscle invasive bladder cancer, Ta and T1

425
00:24:23.900 --> 00:24:27.740
tumors. T2 tumors are when the cancer involves the muscularis

426
00:24:27.780 --> 00:24:30.600
propria. That's muscle-invasive bladder cancer.

427
00:24:31.400 --> 00:24:34.920
And our ability to distinguish clinical T2, T3, and

428
00:24:34.960 --> 00:24:37.140
T4 cancers is somewhat challenging.

429
00:24:37.240 --> 00:24:41.160
Clinical staging of bladder cancer is difficult, but we can tell

430
00:24:41.220 --> 00:24:44.040
if someone has muscle-invasive disease based on

431
00:24:44.080 --> 00:24:48.024
thatTransurethral resection specimen So our

432
00:24:48.084 --> 00:24:51.764
patient asks his urologist what he should do, and

433
00:24:51.924 --> 00:24:55.344
he's told that he should have his bladder removed surgically, a

434
00:24:55.414 --> 00:24:56.144
cystectomy

435
00:24:57.044 --> 00:25:00.544
in an ileal conduit diversion. Of course, when the bladder, the reservoir for

436
00:25:00.704 --> 00:25:04.484
urine, is removed, the urine needs to be diverted, and so

437
00:25:04.804 --> 00:25:08.304
this procedure involves urine draining externally to a bag, to an

438
00:25:08.364 --> 00:25:12.124
ostomy. Radiation therapy is another standard treatment for bladder

439
00:25:12.184 --> 00:25:15.384
cancer. I'm not going to talk about that today just because of lack of time.

440
00:25:17.004 --> 00:25:20.664
So with cystectomy alone, this is a curative

441
00:25:20.724 --> 00:25:24.554
intent surgery for muscle-invasive bladder cancer and cures

442
00:25:24.584 --> 00:25:28.324
many patients, and is a backbone of treatment for muscle-invasive bladder

443
00:25:28.384 --> 00:25:32.284
cancer. But you can see here that the likelihood of cure is very

444
00:25:32.384 --> 00:25:35.464
much dependent on the pathological stage of disease.

445
00:25:35.524 --> 00:25:39.244
So if under the microscope, when the bladder's removed, the cancer is

446
00:25:39.284 --> 00:25:43.184
indeed organ confined, it's indeed pathological T2,

447
00:25:43.224 --> 00:25:47.104
then outcomes are pretty good. But once you have T3 or T4

448
00:25:47.204 --> 00:25:51.104
cancers or microscopic lymph node involvement, the risk of

449
00:25:51.144 --> 00:25:53.364
metastatic recurrence gets much higher.

450
00:25:54.224 --> 00:25:58.164
And historically or traditionally, we've quoted in all comers

451
00:25:58.224 --> 00:26:02.084
with muscle-invasive bladder cancer, approximately 50%

452
00:26:02.144 --> 00:26:04.384
chance of metastatic recurrence with surgery.

453
00:26:04.984 --> 00:26:07.384
So this can be an aggressive disease.

454
00:26:07.824 --> 00:26:11.664
And this vignette really highlights why muscle-invasive bladder

455
00:26:11.744 --> 00:26:14.804
cancer decision-making is complicated.

456
00:26:15.304 --> 00:26:17.224
Our patients are generally older.

457
00:26:17.284 --> 00:26:20.244
The median age of diagnosis in the United States is 76.

458
00:26:20.884 --> 00:26:24.804
Surgery can be life-altering. And despite surgery, there's

459
00:26:24.904 --> 00:26:27.374
a high risk of metastatic recurrence.

460
00:26:27.794 --> 00:26:31.004
And it's really that last point that has led

461
00:26:31.884 --> 00:26:35.444
oncologists, clinical researchers, urologic

462
00:26:35.504 --> 00:26:39.174
oncologists to try and integrate systemic therapy into the

463
00:26:39.244 --> 00:26:41.684
management of muscle-invasive bladder cancer.

464
00:26:42.684 --> 00:26:45.024
And on the somewhat disappointing side,

465
00:26:45.984 --> 00:26:49.724
all of the advances in integrating systemic therapy in

466
00:26:49.784 --> 00:26:53.584
muscle-invasive bladder cancer are essentially encompassed on this single slide.

467
00:26:54.563 --> 00:26:58.364
On the positive slide, many of these advances have occurred in just the past

468
00:26:58.504 --> 00:27:01.444
few years, and so that's really what I'm going to focus on today.

469
00:27:01.504 --> 00:27:03.484
But just a little bit of a historical note.

470
00:27:04.744 --> 00:27:08.584
Multi-agency cisplatin-based chemotherapy shown to be active in patients with

471
00:27:08.624 --> 00:27:12.424
metastatic bladder cancer in the 1980s, integrated

472
00:27:12.484 --> 00:27:16.444
into the neoadjuvant setting, so that's the pre-surgical setting prior

473
00:27:16.544 --> 00:27:20.384
to cystectomy. Around that time, phase two studies showed

474
00:27:20.444 --> 00:27:24.104
promise. Ultimately, phase three studies performed, and then

475
00:27:24.124 --> 00:27:27.914
SWOG 8710, published in 2003, showing a

476
00:27:28.004 --> 00:27:31.944
survival benefit with cisplatin-based chemotherapy prior to surgery.

477
00:27:32.764 --> 00:27:36.224
And that's really what we had for about 30 years with few

478
00:27:36.304 --> 00:27:40.084
advances. And it's not until the era of immune checkpoint

479
00:27:40.164 --> 00:27:42.704
blockade that things really started to change.

480
00:27:42.724 --> 00:27:46.084
And immune checkpoint blockade has many

481
00:27:46.624 --> 00:27:48.784
points of significance in bladder cancer.

482
00:27:49.124 --> 00:27:52.924
Certainly, there's scientific and clinical significance, but there's actually a lot

483
00:27:52.964 --> 00:27:56.944
of practical significance because during these 30 years when

484
00:27:57.004 --> 00:28:00.353
not a whole lot of developments were occurring, there was a lot of

485
00:28:00.404 --> 00:28:03.804
pessimism about drug development in urothelial cancer.

486
00:28:03.844 --> 00:28:07.774
There was this notion that we couldn't accrue trials, that patients were too sick,

487
00:28:08.064 --> 00:28:11.964
that nothing worked. And that created a vicious cycle, and then there was lack

488
00:28:12.004 --> 00:28:15.633
of funding. And really, immune checkpoint blockade showing activity

489
00:28:15.804 --> 00:28:19.684
early in the phase one studies in urothelial cancer started to

490
00:28:19.744 --> 00:28:23.304
open the floodgates of interest really across the board.

491
00:28:23.664 --> 00:28:25.624
And so this represents a turning point.

492
00:28:26.464 --> 00:28:30.133
And in metastatic disease, single agent

493
00:28:30.264 --> 00:28:32.994
PD-1 or PD-L1 blockade has a response rate of about

494
00:28:33.184 --> 00:28:37.154
25%. So it doesn't work in everyone, but of course, like in other

495
00:28:37.164 --> 00:28:40.084
solid tumors, when those drugs work, they work quite well.

496
00:28:40.924 --> 00:28:44.564
And so the logical step of integrating immune checkpoint blockade in

497
00:28:44.624 --> 00:28:48.293
muscle-invasive bladder cancer was to test these therapies in the

498
00:28:48.504 --> 00:28:51.464
adjuvant setting, that is, after patients have surgery

499
00:28:52.364 --> 00:28:56.264
and have features suggestive of a high risk for metastatic

500
00:28:56.304 --> 00:28:58.404
recurrence under the microscope.

501
00:28:58.444 --> 00:29:01.644
And three studies were launched at around the same time, almost

502
00:29:01.784 --> 00:29:05.764
identically designed with a few nuances. The three studies are shown here.

503
00:29:06.304 --> 00:29:09.964
All of them compared a year of immune checkpoint blockade to either

504
00:29:10.144 --> 00:29:13.424
observation or placebo, similar endpoints.

505
00:29:13.454 --> 00:29:17.004
And interestingly, two of the studies met their primary

506
00:29:17.064 --> 00:29:20.844
endpoints, showing an improvement in disease-free survival. One of them didn't.

507
00:29:21.664 --> 00:29:25.244
The study with atezolizumab didn't, but I'm going to circle back to that because

508
00:29:25.284 --> 00:29:27.544
it's been a very important study for the field.

509
00:29:28.504 --> 00:29:32.084
CheckMate 274, which showed an improvement in disease-free

510
00:29:32.164 --> 00:29:36.064
survival with nivolumab, is the only one that's led to an FDA approval

511
00:29:36.104 --> 00:29:36.864
in this space.

512
00:29:37.804 --> 00:29:40.704
So here's the DFS curves with adjuvant nivolumab.

513
00:29:41.084 --> 00:29:44.764
Clearly, this has been an advance in the field integrated into standard

514
00:29:44.844 --> 00:29:48.664
care. But the benefit of nivolumab in the adjuvant setting

515
00:29:49.004 --> 00:29:50.544
is limited by the

516
00:29:51.704 --> 00:29:55.644
challenges of adjuvant therapy for solid tumors

517
00:29:55.684 --> 00:29:59.394
in general, which is that when we give adjuvant therapy, of

518
00:29:59.484 --> 00:30:03.464
course, this is really the only setting in cancer where we're giving

519
00:30:03.484 --> 00:30:07.424
drugs with a relatively narrow therapeutic index to patients who actually don't

520
00:30:07.484 --> 00:30:11.234
have cancer. You can see here, of course, patients treated with

521
00:30:11.244 --> 00:30:11.804
placebo

522
00:30:12.664 --> 00:30:16.034
who are cured with surgery, with or without neoadjuvant therapy.

523
00:30:16.564 --> 00:30:18.184
So these patients don't need treatment.

524
00:30:18.244 --> 00:30:22.064
We could give them all the treatment that we want, and we can only

525
00:30:22.264 --> 00:30:25.224
worsen their outcomes from the standpoint of toxicity.

526
00:30:25.234 --> 00:30:29.044
Of course, these patients in between these lines need treatment and benefit

527
00:30:29.084 --> 00:30:31.724
from it, and the patients above the nivo curve

528
00:30:32.564 --> 00:30:35.024
need adjuvant treatment, but they don't benefit.

529
00:30:35.344 --> 00:30:39.284
And so one would be hard-pressed to find a setting where we need biomarkers

530
00:30:39.364 --> 00:30:41.644
more than we need in the adjuvant setting.

531
00:30:42.164 --> 00:30:46.084
And I say biomarkers rather than biomarker because I think

532
00:30:46.124 --> 00:30:49.404
we have a double biomarker problem in the adjuvant setting.

533
00:30:50.084 --> 00:30:53.284
We have a single biomarker problem in the metastatic setting, arguably.

534
00:30:53.324 --> 00:30:56.644
We have a bunch of drugs. We don't know which patients respond to which drugs, and

535
00:30:56.684 --> 00:31:00.660
we need biomarkers to determine the right drugs for the right patient.In

536
00:31:00.700 --> 00:31:02.620
the adjuvant setting, we have this double problem.

537
00:31:03.000 --> 00:31:06.060
Not only don't we know what drugs work for which patients, we don't even

538
00:31:06.880 --> 00:31:10.660
really know who needs treatment. And this gets conflated because, of

539
00:31:10.760 --> 00:31:14.460
course, you can't benefit from treatment if you don't need treatment, but you

540
00:31:14.540 --> 00:31:16.999
can need treatment and not benefit from it.

541
00:31:17.360 --> 00:31:21.170
And so I would argue that we need two sets of biomarkers to answer these

542
00:31:21.200 --> 00:31:24.280
questions. I don't think they're necessarily going to be the same.

543
00:31:24.700 --> 00:31:28.600
Finding biomarkers to determine who benefits from particular drugs

544
00:31:28.640 --> 00:31:32.420
has been a little bit more elusive, but we're getting much closer to

545
00:31:32.460 --> 00:31:35.620
defining who needs treatment in the adjuvant setting.

546
00:31:35.670 --> 00:31:39.600
And of course, what's been most promising has been cfDNA

547
00:31:40.000 --> 00:31:43.260
as a measure of minimal residual disease.

548
00:31:43.860 --> 00:31:47.740
So I told you that that study with atezolizumab in IMvigor10 didn't

549
00:31:47.780 --> 00:31:51.520
meet its primary endpoint, and so the investigators

550
00:31:51.640 --> 00:31:55.260
did a molecular autopsy of that study, if you will, and they asked the

551
00:31:55.300 --> 00:31:59.060
question, would the results have been different if they were able to

552
00:31:59.100 --> 00:32:01.360
determine who actually needed adjuvant treatment?

553
00:32:01.460 --> 00:32:05.440
So they applied a tumor-informed ctDNA test, the Signatera assay,

554
00:32:06.080 --> 00:32:09.880
retrospectively to this study. And now you see the disease-free

555
00:32:09.960 --> 00:32:13.840
survival curves, and here's patients with undetectable ctDNA at a

556
00:32:13.900 --> 00:32:15.920
single time point after cystectomy.

557
00:32:16.280 --> 00:32:18.700
Here's patients with detectable ctDNA.

558
00:32:19.250 --> 00:32:23.180
And you see here now there seems to be a benefit from atezolizumab

559
00:32:23.220 --> 00:32:26.820
in blue versus observation in red.

560
00:32:27.720 --> 00:32:30.470
So this is retrospective data, of course.

561
00:32:30.620 --> 00:32:34.360
And what these investigators did is really how this should work, a

562
00:32:34.400 --> 00:32:38.300
negative study trying to dissect why the study

563
00:32:38.340 --> 00:32:42.200
didn't turn out positive, and then designing a study to test that

564
00:32:43.240 --> 00:32:46.670
concept. And so that's just what they did, and they did a prospective

565
00:32:46.800 --> 00:32:50.660
study seeking to determine whether or not ctDNA

566
00:32:50.720 --> 00:32:54.340
would have changed the results. And so the design was almost

567
00:32:54.440 --> 00:32:57.200
identical to IMvigor10. This is IMvigor11.

568
00:32:57.680 --> 00:33:01.390
But what they did here was enroll patients after surgery, similar

569
00:33:01.420 --> 00:33:04.740
pathologic features under the microscope, and patients underwent

570
00:33:04.780 --> 00:33:08.520
ctDNA testing. And if they had detectable ctDNA,

571
00:33:08.660 --> 00:33:11.840
they were randomized to atezolizumab versus placebo.

572
00:33:12.400 --> 00:33:15.920
And if they had undetectable ctDNA, then they had serial

573
00:33:15.980 --> 00:33:18.179
testing every six weeks for a year.

574
00:33:18.720 --> 00:33:22.060
And if at any time the test converted from

575
00:33:22.120 --> 00:33:25.840
undetectable to detectable, then they entered the randomization.

576
00:33:25.920 --> 00:33:29.500
And I should mention that same assay, Signatera

577
00:33:29.580 --> 00:33:33.320
tumor-informed testing. Interestingly, the study was designed

578
00:33:33.380 --> 00:33:37.140
to test whether or not atezo led to an improvement in

579
00:33:37.180 --> 00:33:40.660
outcomes compared to placebo in patients with

580
00:33:40.680 --> 00:33:44.560
ctDNA detectable assays, regardless of when that occurred,

581
00:33:44.700 --> 00:33:48.420
either immediately after surgery in the traditional adjuvant setting or

582
00:33:48.520 --> 00:33:50.020
during that year of surveillance.

583
00:33:50.420 --> 00:33:54.400
So all that data was pooled, but then they analyzed the population

584
00:33:54.560 --> 00:33:58.190
separately as well. So here's the flow of patients in that study.

585
00:33:58.220 --> 00:34:01.780
Six hundred and seven patients. Four hundred and fifty-nine had undetectable

586
00:34:01.900 --> 00:34:05.600
assays after surgery. Among those during that follow-up,

587
00:34:06.340 --> 00:34:09.740
22% had conversion from undetectable to

588
00:34:09.821 --> 00:34:13.520
detectable. So an undetectable test right after

589
00:34:13.640 --> 00:34:17.600
surgery, unfortunately, with the assays currently available, certainly doesn't

590
00:34:17.640 --> 00:34:20.740
mean that patients are "out of the woods."

591
00:34:22.600 --> 00:34:26.321
But thankfully, only 4% of patients on this

592
00:34:26.361 --> 00:34:30.341
study during that follow-up developed metastatic disease

593
00:34:30.400 --> 00:34:34.330
on scan prior to an assay converting from

594
00:34:34.380 --> 00:34:38.310
negative to positive or undetectable to detectable, suggesting that

595
00:34:38.321 --> 00:34:42.020
there is potentially this window of opportunity for intervention

596
00:34:42.060 --> 00:34:45.580
before detecting radiographic metastatic disease.

597
00:34:45.611 --> 00:34:47.321
And here's the outcomes on the study.

598
00:34:47.420 --> 00:34:51.140
The top are patients who had detectable ctDNA right after surgery.

599
00:34:51.480 --> 00:34:55.020
The bottom are patients who had detectable ctDNA sometime during that

600
00:34:55.120 --> 00:34:58.880
follow-up. You see that disease-free survival and overall

601
00:34:58.890 --> 00:35:02.720
survival improved in both of those populations

602
00:35:02.780 --> 00:35:05.880
with atezolizumab versus placebo.

603
00:35:05.920 --> 00:35:08.600
And so this study's important for a number of reasons.

604
00:35:08.740 --> 00:35:12.260
One, because it prospectively validates the findings from

605
00:35:12.300 --> 00:35:15.460
IMvigor10 and establishes clinical utility.

606
00:35:15.620 --> 00:35:19.480
I think one of the first demonstrations of clinical utility

607
00:35:19.540 --> 00:35:22.279
for ctDNA in terms of adjuvant decision-making.

608
00:35:22.670 --> 00:35:25.580
And second, I think this is probably the first

609
00:35:25.760 --> 00:35:29.580
demonstration that molecular recurrence of bladder

610
00:35:29.680 --> 00:35:33.540
cancer is a clinically intervenable disease

611
00:35:33.680 --> 00:35:36.220
state that can lead to improvement in outcomes.

612
00:35:36.260 --> 00:35:39.920
And obviously, this has implications for drug development as well.

613
00:35:41.020 --> 00:35:44.880
In the US Cooperative Group System, we've taken

614
00:35:44.960 --> 00:35:48.360
a slightly different approach to this question, arguing that

615
00:35:48.400 --> 00:35:51.980
nivolumab was already approved by the FDA for adjuvant therapy.

616
00:35:52.460 --> 00:35:54.760
And if you look at those survival curves

617
00:35:55.960 --> 00:35:59.560
with adjuvant atezolizumab in patients with detectable

618
00:35:59.570 --> 00:36:03.100
ctDNA, obviously, we have to do better than that.

619
00:36:03.110 --> 00:36:06.880
And so we're asking two questions in this study called MODERN.

620
00:36:06.900 --> 00:36:10.430
We're asking an escalation question and a de-escalation

621
00:36:10.540 --> 00:36:14.260
question. And the way this trial works, patients are enrolled

622
00:36:14.580 --> 00:36:18.480
after cystectomy, similar pathological features to the other

623
00:36:18.560 --> 00:36:22.260
studies. They undergo Signatera testing, tumor-informed

624
00:36:22.300 --> 00:36:26.180
ctDNA testing. If they have detectable ctDNA,

625
00:36:26.300 --> 00:36:29.960
they're randomized to nivolumab versus nivolumab plus a

626
00:36:30.020 --> 00:36:32.950
LAG-3 inhibitor, so seeking to escalate treatment.

627
00:36:33.410 --> 00:36:37.270
This part of the study employs a seamless Phase 2, 3 design, and

628
00:36:37.300 --> 00:36:40.120
the Phase 2 endpoint is ctDNA clearance.

629
00:36:40.620 --> 00:36:44.440
So we hope to establish perhaps the first time that we can use ctDNA

630
00:36:44.500 --> 00:36:48.460
clearance as a way to screen the activity of novel regimens in the adjuvant

631
00:36:48.560 --> 00:36:52.200
setting. And in patients with undetectable ctDNA, we're

632
00:36:52.320 --> 00:36:55.840
asking, is a surveillance, a watch-and-wait

633
00:36:55.880 --> 00:36:58.740
approach with treatment upon molecular recurrence

634
00:36:59.540 --> 00:37:03.100
non-inferior to immediate adjuvant treatment in all?

635
00:37:03.180 --> 00:37:06.880
So this has been enrolling for about two years, and is

636
00:37:06.920 --> 00:37:10.856
open throughout the United States.While this is occurring in the

637
00:37:10.956 --> 00:37:14.756
adjuvant setting, of course, drug development continues in the metastatic setting,

638
00:37:14.816 --> 00:37:18.556
and we heard already from Dr. Faltes about the combination of enfortumab

639
00:37:18.616 --> 00:37:22.416
vedotin and pembrolizumab. So this is an antibody drug conjugate

640
00:37:22.476 --> 00:37:26.016
directed against nectin-4 with an MMAE payload

641
00:37:26.076 --> 00:37:29.726
combined with PD-1 blockade. In the metastatic setting,

642
00:37:30.016 --> 00:37:33.706
results in response rates of about 60% to 70%,

643
00:37:33.796 --> 00:37:36.906
really the highest that we've seen in urothelial cancer.

644
00:37:37.176 --> 00:37:41.096
A blue platinum-based chemotherapy out of the water in a phase

645
00:37:41.136 --> 00:37:44.516
three study that was presented in 2023 and really

646
00:37:44.616 --> 00:37:48.156
has become the standard of care for metastatic urothelial

647
00:37:48.176 --> 00:37:51.906
cancer. And of course, the logical thing is then to take that regimen and

648
00:37:51.936 --> 00:37:55.536
apply it to the muscle-invasive bladder cancer setting.

649
00:37:55.596 --> 00:37:59.536
So that's been done in two studies now, one study in patients

650
00:37:59.676 --> 00:38:03.436
who were considered ineligible to receive cisplatin-based chemotherapy,

651
00:38:04.596 --> 00:38:08.276
the only perioperative systemic therapy that has shown benefit

652
00:38:08.336 --> 00:38:12.116
historically. So that randomization was EV pembro,

653
00:38:12.656 --> 00:38:16.276
followed by cystectomy, followed by adjuvant EV pembro

654
00:38:16.316 --> 00:38:18.946
versus cystectomy alone, and then

655
00:38:19.176 --> 00:38:22.996
KEYNOTE-B15 compared neoadjuvant cisplatin-based

656
00:38:23.076 --> 00:38:26.676
chemotherapy to this perioperative EV pembro

657
00:38:26.736 --> 00:38:27.216
approach,

658
00:38:28.036 --> 00:38:31.256
and both of the studies have now read out over the last year.

659
00:38:31.736 --> 00:38:35.716
You can see the event-free survival curves, the primary endpoint of the

660
00:38:35.856 --> 00:38:39.396
study at the bottom, and you see that both studies show a marked

661
00:38:39.456 --> 00:38:43.156
improvement in outcomes with EV pembro in the perioperative setting

662
00:38:43.496 --> 00:38:47.276
versus either cisplatin-based neoadjuvant therapy or cystectomy

663
00:38:47.336 --> 00:38:51.296
alone, depending on the study. And then here you see the pathological

664
00:38:51.336 --> 00:38:52.856
response rates on the study.

665
00:38:53.796 --> 00:38:57.596
So cystectomy alone, a path CR rate, meaning that, of

666
00:38:57.656 --> 00:39:00.576
course, when the bladder's removed and analyzed under the microscope, there's no

667
00:39:00.596 --> 00:39:02.416
evidence of cancer under the microscope.

668
00:39:02.916 --> 00:39:06.556
So with cystectomy alone, there's about a 9% chance of that

669
00:39:06.596 --> 00:39:09.786
happening. How does that happen? Well, remember I told you that transurethral

670
00:39:09.816 --> 00:39:13.516
resection is performed. Sometimes that gets rid of all the

671
00:39:13.576 --> 00:39:17.336
cancer. So about a 9% chance with cystectomy

672
00:39:17.396 --> 00:39:21.296
alone, but 57.1% path CR rate with EV

673
00:39:21.356 --> 00:39:25.336
pembro, very similar in KEYNOTE-B15 and much better

674
00:39:25.376 --> 00:39:28.676
than older chemotherapy. So when we see a path

675
00:39:28.716 --> 00:39:32.676
CR in the clinic, as medical oncologists, we're quite happy to see

676
00:39:32.756 --> 00:39:35.536
it. It correlates with better survival.

677
00:39:35.916 --> 00:39:37.456
You can see in the curves here.

678
00:39:38.476 --> 00:39:42.296
And of course, patients look at us like we're crazy when we say, "Great

679
00:39:42.336 --> 00:39:46.036
news, there's no cancer in your bladder," after their bladder has already been

680
00:39:46.076 --> 00:39:49.456
removed. And so that really begs the question, what's happening?

681
00:39:49.466 --> 00:39:52.276
And who are these patients in this top curve here?

682
00:39:52.296 --> 00:39:55.286
And I would argue that there's three groups of patients, right?

683
00:39:55.296 --> 00:39:59.196
There are these patients who have local disease and micrometastatic

684
00:39:59.216 --> 00:40:01.716
disease that's eradicated with systemic therapy.

685
00:40:02.256 --> 00:40:06.036
There's patients who have no micrometastatic disease but have local disease that's

686
00:40:06.076 --> 00:40:06.836
eradicated.

687
00:40:07.636 --> 00:40:11.156
And then there is that group of patients where the systemic therapy did nothing and

688
00:40:11.316 --> 00:40:13.936
the transurethral resection got rid of local tumor.

689
00:40:14.636 --> 00:40:18.436
Regardless of how this is achieved, if TURBT

690
00:40:18.476 --> 00:40:22.396
plus systemic therapy can get rid of muscle-invasive bladder cancer,

691
00:40:22.796 --> 00:40:26.296
then can this be an effective standard treatment for

692
00:40:26.536 --> 00:40:27.956
muscle-invasive bladder cancer?

693
00:40:28.516 --> 00:40:31.956
And that's a question that's been sort of bandied about in the

694
00:40:32.416 --> 00:40:36.316
field for 30 plus years. We started thinking about this, the Fox

695
00:40:36.656 --> 00:40:40.616
Chase group started thinking about this probably about 12 years ago

696
00:40:40.976 --> 00:40:44.496
in a more serious way to really try and dissect what are the

697
00:40:44.516 --> 00:40:46.766
barriers to achieving this in the clinic.

698
00:40:47.216 --> 00:40:50.566
And we outlined these five barriers to implementation of

699
00:40:50.596 --> 00:40:53.776
TURBT plus systemic therapy as curative

700
00:40:53.816 --> 00:40:56.486
bladder-sparing treatment for muscle-invasive bladder cancer.

701
00:40:57.096 --> 00:41:00.686
One, we really didn't have prospective studies. That's the biggest barrier.

702
00:41:00.716 --> 00:41:04.536
The second is that this notion of a clinical response to treatment

703
00:41:04.676 --> 00:41:08.636
had never been really defined. What assessments are needed?

704
00:41:08.956 --> 00:41:11.216
What is a clinical complete response?

705
00:41:12.756 --> 00:41:15.696
Our systemic therapies were suboptimal, of course.

706
00:41:16.536 --> 00:41:20.496
And then there's this limited understanding of what happens with

707
00:41:20.536 --> 00:41:24.466
a delayed cystectomy. So if a patient achieves a, quote-unquote, clinical complete

708
00:41:24.536 --> 00:41:28.096
response, and their bladder's left intact, and they have a later local

709
00:41:28.136 --> 00:41:31.606
recurrence and require cystectomy, have we missed a window of

710
00:41:31.636 --> 00:41:35.426
opportunity for a cure? And then absence of biomarkers to

711
00:41:35.476 --> 00:41:39.236
refine decision-making. So over the past decade, I think we're

712
00:41:39.296 --> 00:41:42.996
making a lot of progress in the first three, and we're making some

713
00:41:43.076 --> 00:41:46.516
progress in the last two, and I'm going to touch on this during the remainder.

714
00:41:47.136 --> 00:41:51.036
So our first trial at attempting to determine whether or not this was a

715
00:41:51.056 --> 00:41:54.436
viable strategy, we designed in 2016.

716
00:41:54.476 --> 00:41:58.216
In this study, patients with muscle-invasive bladder cancer got four cycles

717
00:41:58.296 --> 00:42:02.176
of chemotherapy plus PD-1 blockade and then underwent a

718
00:42:02.256 --> 00:42:06.216
series of assessments, including repeat cystoscopy and biopsies

719
00:42:06.256 --> 00:42:09.996
of the bladder. And if all of those assessments showed no evidence of

720
00:42:10.056 --> 00:42:13.976
cancer, patients had the choice to have no cystectomy and receive

721
00:42:14.036 --> 00:42:17.396
additional maintenance immune checkpoint blockade or to have a

722
00:42:17.416 --> 00:42:21.016
cystectomy. If there was no clinical complete response, then we

723
00:42:21.056 --> 00:42:23.716
recommended proceeding with standard cystectomy.

724
00:42:24.176 --> 00:42:28.116
The co-primary endpoints were to define the clinical complete response rate because

725
00:42:28.176 --> 00:42:32.016
clinical complete response had never been defined before, and to determine

726
00:42:32.026 --> 00:42:35.216
the performance of a clinical complete response in

727
00:42:35.276 --> 00:42:37.556
predicting longer-term outcomes.

728
00:42:38.536 --> 00:42:41.016
So 76 patients enrolled on this study.

729
00:42:41.116 --> 00:42:44.196
The clinical complete response rate was 43%.

730
00:42:44.616 --> 00:42:48.236
You can see here that among 33 patients with a clinical CR,

731
00:42:48.436 --> 00:42:51.216
only one opted for immediate cystectomy.

732
00:42:51.256 --> 00:42:53.576
Patients voted with their feet here.

733
00:42:54.076 --> 00:42:56.855
And here you see the outcomes on this study.

734
00:42:56.916 --> 00:43:00.826
So here's metastasis-free survival stratified by clinical

735
00:43:00.936 --> 00:43:04.908
complete response.At the landmark time point of clinical restaging.

736
00:43:05.348 --> 00:43:09.258
If nothing else, clinical complete response is a prognostic

737
00:43:09.268 --> 00:43:13.168
biomarker here. So really separates patients at higher

738
00:43:13.228 --> 00:43:17.107
versus lower risk of developing metastatic disease.

739
00:43:17.128 --> 00:43:21.108
