00:58:02.784 --> 00:58:06.444
transition, causing cells to enter a state of what we call late

978
00:58:06.664 --> 00:58:07.684
S phase stasis.

979
00:58:08.854 --> 00:58:12.704
So we then asked, can this transient A3A exposure is

980
00:58:12.744 --> 00:58:15.384
sufficient to induce lasting changes in the cell?

981
00:58:15.624 --> 00:58:18.804
So can we turn off A3A and then continue to see these changes?

982
00:58:19.404 --> 00:58:23.074
And we exposed these 5637 cells to 48 hours of A3A

983
00:58:23.104 --> 00:58:26.864
expression, withdrew doxycycline, and then monitored cell cycle

984
00:58:26.884 --> 00:58:30.544
dynamics and vimentin levels for 168

985
00:58:30.624 --> 00:58:34.184
hours after dox withdrawal. And as you can see, the cells

986
00:58:34.224 --> 00:58:38.004
continue to upregulate markers of plasticity, such as vimentin,

987
00:58:38.484 --> 00:58:42.333
and to have markers of this persistent S-phase stasis for a

988
00:58:42.404 --> 00:58:44.744
number of hours after we withdraw A3A.

989
00:58:45.904 --> 00:58:49.304
Okay, so now we know that A3A induces double-strand

990
00:58:49.324 --> 00:58:53.104
breaks in S-phase stasis, but what is the mechanistic link

991
00:58:53.124 --> 00:58:55.684
between these processes and SOX2 upregulation?

992
00:58:56.314 --> 00:58:59.854
Is it a state of A3A chromatin remodeling,

993
00:58:59.944 --> 00:59:03.464
perhaps, or is it another transcription factor that

994
00:59:03.504 --> 00:59:07.304
upregulates SOX2? And to answer this, we performed chromatin

995
00:59:07.344 --> 00:59:11.214
accessibility profiling, so ATAC-seq on these 5637 cells

996
00:59:11.744 --> 00:59:14.624
after either one cycle, so one exposure or six

997
00:59:14.684 --> 00:59:18.544
transient exposures of A3A. And

998
00:59:18.684 --> 00:59:22.544
on the left, you can see the tornado plot that shows the A3A persistent

999
00:59:22.604 --> 00:59:26.544
changes in chromatin accessibility profiles in both conditions,

1000
00:59:26.963 --> 00:59:30.904
suggesting that these accessibility changes are maintained across cell

1001
00:59:30.944 --> 00:59:34.844
divisions. And we saw that there is a marked increase

1002
00:59:34.884 --> 00:59:37.504
in chromatin accessibility at the SOX2 promoter.

1003
00:59:38.464 --> 00:59:42.324
And we asked, well, what is another transcription factor that

1004
00:59:42.384 --> 00:59:46.244
might be binding to the SOX2 promoter that is upregulated by

1005
00:59:46.324 --> 00:59:49.364
A3A double-strand breaks and cell cycle stasis?

1006
00:59:50.184 --> 00:59:54.024
And the answer is FOXM1. And to us, this

1007
00:59:54.084 --> 00:59:57.944
made sense because FOXM1 is a master regulator

1008
00:59:58.604 --> 01:00:00.964
of the DNA damage repair response.

1009
01:00:01.264 --> 01:00:04.824
It increases during the S phase. So that made sense to us.

1010
01:00:05.184 --> 01:00:09.024
And indeed, when we looked at our ChIP-qPCR experiment here, we

1011
01:00:09.044 --> 01:00:12.904
see an 11-fold higher FOXM1 occupancy at the SOX2

1012
01:00:12.944 --> 01:00:16.924
promoter in the A3A exposed cells, but not in the controls.

1013
01:00:17.054 --> 01:00:20.884
And we can see that this goes away when we use a DMNA stead

1014
01:00:21.044 --> 01:00:23.564
E72A mutant of A3A.

1015
01:00:25.644 --> 01:00:28.384
We also clearly confirmed this at the protein level.

1016
01:00:28.484 --> 01:00:32.404
So again, here you can look at the 5637 cell line and a breast cancer cell

1017
01:00:32.464 --> 01:00:35.904
line, and you can see that A3A exposure increases

1018
01:00:35.964 --> 01:00:39.784
FOXM1, SOX2, and vimentin at the protein level.

1019
01:00:41.444 --> 01:00:44.904
Interestingly, we observed this wasn't the only change in the

1020
01:00:44.924 --> 01:00:48.764
regulatory regions of SOX2. We also saw a marked increase in

1021
01:00:48.804 --> 01:00:52.484
chromatin accessibility at a SOX2 distal super enhancer

1022
01:00:52.584 --> 01:00:56.224
element that's previously shown to be necessary and sufficient for

1023
01:00:56.244 --> 01:00:59.300
SOX2 expression.And we know that

1024
01:00:59.600 --> 01:01:03.160
SOX2 acts as its own transcription factor, so it

1025
01:01:03.180 --> 01:01:07.000
sustains its own expression by binding directly to its

1026
01:01:07.340 --> 01:01:11.260
own enhancer to reinforce transcription, and this cooperates

1027
01:01:11.300 --> 01:01:14.720
with the persistent changes in chromatin accessibility at the SOX2

1028
01:01:14.739 --> 01:01:17.980
promoter and distal enhancer to lock

1029
01:01:18.040 --> 01:01:21.260
these A3A-exposed cells into this stable

1030
01:01:21.680 --> 01:01:25.260
SOX2 high state independent of any ongoing A3A

1031
01:01:25.280 --> 01:01:25.860
activity.

1032
01:01:27.400 --> 01:01:30.420
So, one could say, well, this is all with

1033
01:01:30.979 --> 01:01:33.940
exogenously expressed A3A. This is quite artificial.

1034
01:01:34.900 --> 01:01:38.800
And we can know we can induce endogenous A3A with interferon.

1035
01:01:38.830 --> 01:01:42.420
And when we did that, we can see that we can also upregulate SOX2 in

1036
01:01:42.460 --> 01:01:46.320
multiple cell lines, and when we knock out A3A with CRISPR,

1037
01:01:46.460 --> 01:01:49.940
that this effect completely is really abrogated.

1038
01:01:51.040 --> 01:01:54.840
And importantly, when we overexpressed a deaminase

1039
01:01:54.900 --> 01:01:56.600
dead E72A

1040
01:01:58.120 --> 01:02:01.760
mutant, A3A mutant, we see that the SOX2 and the FOXM1

1041
01:02:02.400 --> 01:02:05.980
downstream effects are not seen, suggesting that the

1042
01:02:06.020 --> 01:02:08.620
deaminase activity of A3A is required.

1043
01:02:09.580 --> 01:02:13.260
So to put all that together, we coined a term for this state, which we

1044
01:02:13.300 --> 01:02:16.900
call DASP or deaminase activated cell cycle

1045
01:02:16.920 --> 01:02:20.860
stasis and reprogramming. And this is our proposed model

1046
01:02:20.920 --> 01:02:24.540
for the sequence of molecular events that occur in DASP.

1047
01:02:25.020 --> 01:02:28.540
First, the A3A deaminase activity generates

1048
01:02:28.560 --> 01:02:32.470
double-strand breaks, inducing cell cycle stasis in the late S phase,

1049
01:02:32.720 --> 01:02:36.119
and this opens a permissive temporal window for chromatin

1050
01:02:36.160 --> 01:02:40.120
remodeling at the SOX2 locus, increasing accessibility

1051
01:02:40.130 --> 01:02:43.500
at both the proximal promoter and the distal enhancer, as I showed

1052
01:02:43.560 --> 01:02:47.430
you. FOXM1 binds to the SOX2 promoter and directly

1053
01:02:47.500 --> 01:02:50.860
activates transcription, while the distal enhancer provides

1054
01:02:50.900 --> 01:02:54.620
additional transactivation. And this establishes

1055
01:02:54.720 --> 01:02:58.190
a feed-forward circuit that locks the cells into this

1056
01:02:58.240 --> 01:02:59.399
SOX2 high state.

1057
01:03:00.740 --> 01:03:04.420
And one of the interesting aspects of DASP that I want to highlight is that it

1058
01:03:04.460 --> 01:03:08.180
shows us that it's a mechanism by which a transient

1059
01:03:08.220 --> 01:03:12.160
genotoxic stress or double-strand break caused by A3A can be

1060
01:03:12.200 --> 01:03:15.870
converted into a heritable long-lasting cell state with

1061
01:03:15.900 --> 01:03:19.840
important phenotypic consequences, as I will show you in a minute.

1062
01:03:19.900 --> 01:03:22.650
So what are these functional consequences?

1063
01:03:23.080 --> 01:03:26.969
One of them is one that I showed you already, which is drug resistance,

1064
01:03:27.060 --> 01:03:30.360
where you can see that these cancer cells that are exhibiting DASP

1065
01:03:30.400 --> 01:03:34.340
have a fitness advantage and survive better under

1066
01:03:34.380 --> 01:03:35.200
drug selection.

1067
01:03:36.160 --> 01:03:40.100
Another phenotype is increased migration, and we have measured

1068
01:03:40.120 --> 01:03:43.220
this with live-cell imaging that shows increased migration in the

1069
01:03:43.400 --> 01:03:46.680
5637 cells exposed to A3A compared to

1070
01:03:46.720 --> 01:03:47.440
controls.

1071
01:03:50.080 --> 01:03:53.980
And this one is my favorite. So this is live-cell imaging of

1072
01:03:54.040 --> 01:03:58.020
a 3D Matrigel spheroid invasion assay of a different cell line called

1073
01:03:58.120 --> 01:04:02.100
UMUC3 that is exposed to A3A, and

1074
01:04:02.120 --> 01:04:06.040
you can easily appreciate that by the end of the video, which is day

1075
01:04:06.080 --> 01:04:09.780
18, the A3A-exposed cells have

1076
01:04:09.820 --> 01:04:13.140
4.7 times larger invading

1077
01:04:13.240 --> 01:04:15.260
area compared to the controls.

1078
01:04:27.900 --> 01:04:31.880
And when we performed confocal microscopy of these

1079
01:04:32.200 --> 01:04:35.580
spheroids, we see that the cells at the invasive front

1080
01:04:36.520 --> 01:04:40.500
consistently show higher SOX2 expression and morphologically

1081
01:04:40.510 --> 01:04:42.360
are very different from the controls.

1082
01:04:43.260 --> 01:04:47.060
I was just telling Phil, if you look at the bottom, when I looked at these for the

1083
01:04:47.100 --> 01:04:50.360
first time, I thought that the scale bar was wrong, but it's not.

1084
01:04:50.440 --> 01:04:54.300
These are really morphologically very different, and they're quite

1085
01:04:54.440 --> 01:04:56.740
invasive as we are observing here.

1086
01:04:57.880 --> 01:05:01.620
So now that we have this new cell state,

1087
01:05:01.900 --> 01:05:05.840
one might ask, well, how do we know that this is truly a distinct reprogrammed

1088
01:05:05.960 --> 01:05:08.540
state and not just a generic cell stress response?

1089
01:05:09.100 --> 01:05:12.020
And to test this, we experimentally induced A3A,

1090
01:05:12.900 --> 01:05:16.740
treated the same cells, so other cells, same cell line,

1091
01:05:16.819 --> 01:05:20.690
but different treatment, with either doxorubicin to

1092
01:05:20.720 --> 01:05:24.630
induce DNA damage, tunicamycin to induce ER stress, or

1093
01:05:24.640 --> 01:05:27.900
TGF-beta, which is a canonical inducer of EMT.

1094
01:05:27.920 --> 01:05:31.760
And we performed RNA sequencing, and as you can see here,

1095
01:05:31.800 --> 01:05:35.740
the transcriptomes of the A3A-exposed cells clustered quite separately from

1096
01:05:35.800 --> 01:05:39.780
the other stress responses in the principal component analysis.

1097
01:05:41.380 --> 01:05:42.020
Importantly,

1098
01:05:42.840 --> 01:05:46.800
confirming the role of the FOXM1 SOX2 axis here, we can see that

1099
01:05:46.940 --> 01:05:50.920
A3A exposure is the only condition that co-activates both

1100
01:05:50.980 --> 01:05:53.300
FOXM1 and SOX2 targets.

1101
01:05:54.500 --> 01:05:58.010
And we further validated these results at the protein level by measuring

1102
01:05:58.020 --> 01:06:00.920
FOXM1 and SOX2 in cells exposed to either A3A,

1103
01:06:01.420 --> 01:06:04.160
doxorubicin, TGF-beta, or tunicamycin.

1104
01:06:04.200 --> 01:06:07.540
And again, DASP is the only state that upregulates both

1105
01:06:07.580 --> 01:06:08.940
FOXM1 and SOX2.

1106
01:06:09.980 --> 01:06:13.780
We developed a DASP transcriptomic signature to apply to clinical

1107
01:06:13.790 --> 01:06:17.660
samples that combine four gene sets that represents its

1108
01:06:17.720 --> 01:06:21.270
salient biological features, the SOX2 target genes,

1109
01:06:21.360 --> 01:06:24.329
FOXM1 target genes, S phase genes, and

1110
01:06:24.460 --> 01:06:28.120
epithelial-mesenchymal plasticity genes into

1111
01:06:28.200 --> 01:06:31.700
a single normalized enrichment score.

1112
01:06:31.740 --> 01:06:35.460
And when we applied this DASP score to the TGA pan-cancer

1113
01:06:36.000 --> 01:06:39.980
human atlas, we see that tumors with high A3A

1114
01:06:40.380 --> 01:06:44.300
mRNA expression had significantly higher DASP scores compared to

1115
01:06:44.340 --> 01:06:48.320
the A3A-low tumors and higher enrichment of the FOXM1

1116
01:06:48.360 --> 01:06:49.640
and SOX2 targets.

1117
01:06:51.300 --> 01:06:54.320
And patients with those tumors had higher DASP scores--

1118
01:06:55.380 --> 01:06:58.420
patients with tumors who have higher DASP scores have worse

1119
01:06:58.860 --> 01:07:02.360
progression-free survival to a number of therapies and worse overall

1120
01:07:02.440 --> 01:07:06.188
survival.So can we reverse this? And can we

1121
01:07:06.228 --> 01:07:09.728
target SOX2, which we again mentioned is an important

1122
01:07:09.788 --> 01:07:13.408
mediator here, to reverse DASP? And we tested a SOX2 by

1123
01:07:13.528 --> 01:07:17.168
PROTAC, which is a SOX2 binding nanobody

1124
01:07:17.308 --> 01:07:21.288
fused to a modified E3 ubiquitin ligase that selectively degrades

1125
01:07:21.298 --> 01:07:25.068
SOX2, and we can see that this sensitizes

1126
01:07:25.128 --> 01:07:27.908
A3 exposed cells to trastuzumab

1127
01:07:27.928 --> 01:07:30.748
deruxtecan, which is a HER2

1128
01:07:30.758 --> 01:07:34.268
targeting antibody drug conjugate with a

1129
01:07:34.358 --> 01:07:36.148
topoisomerase inhibitor payload.

1130
01:07:36.228 --> 01:07:40.188
So this demonstrates how SOX2 inhibition is a promising

1131
01:07:40.248 --> 01:07:43.128
strategy for reversing DASP mediated drug resistance.

1132
01:07:44.308 --> 01:07:48.288
Now I'll switch gears to the second part of my talk, which is how do we use window

1133
01:07:48.298 --> 01:07:52.267
of opportunity and co-clinical trial designs to identify

1134
01:07:52.328 --> 01:07:54.328
rational sequential drug combinations?

1135
01:07:55.088 --> 01:07:58.508
One of the questions that arises from having multiple effective

1136
01:07:58.588 --> 01:08:02.488
therapies is what is the best mechanistically grounded sequence for

1137
01:08:02.548 --> 01:08:03.188
these drugs?

1138
01:08:04.598 --> 01:08:08.468
We have developed a co-clinical trial framework that

1139
01:08:08.508 --> 01:08:12.328
allows us to define the biology of an initial therapy in

1140
01:08:12.368 --> 01:08:15.768
patients in a window of opportunity study design, and then

1141
01:08:15.808 --> 01:08:19.119
test rational sequential strategies in patient-derived

1142
01:08:19.228 --> 01:08:22.548
organoids from the same trial and from the same patients.

1143
01:08:22.628 --> 01:08:23.148
And I'll show you

1144
01:08:23.968 --> 01:08:27.829
an example of how we did this. So this is in CLONIVA,

1145
01:08:27.909 --> 01:08:31.168
which is an investigator initiated window of opportunity trial

1146
01:08:31.728 --> 01:08:35.449
that we completed at Weill Cornell, and it's in patients

1147
01:08:35.568 --> 01:08:39.228
with resectable muscle invasive bladder cancer who were cisplatin

1148
01:08:39.308 --> 01:08:41.208
ineligible or declined cisplatin.

1149
01:08:41.808 --> 01:08:45.288
These patients received four to eight weeks of oral abemaciclib, which is a

1150
01:08:45.348 --> 01:08:49.308
CDK4/6 inhibitor, and we collected paired pre and post-treatment

1151
01:08:49.388 --> 01:08:52.508
tissues from these patients with serial plasma samples.

1152
01:08:53.108 --> 01:08:57.068
We had 20 patients enrolled, 16 patients underwent cystectomy and

1153
01:08:57.108 --> 01:08:59.268
were evaluable for the primary endpoint.

1154
01:09:00.928 --> 01:09:04.579
And to define the biological effects and the therapeutic vulnerabilities that

1155
01:09:04.628 --> 01:09:08.608
arise from these effects, after abemaciclib treatment, we

1156
01:09:08.648 --> 01:09:12.568
performed whole exome sequencing, RNA sequencing, and spatial single-cell

1157
01:09:13.268 --> 01:09:17.029
imaging mass cytometry comparing the pre and post-treatment tissue

1158
01:09:17.128 --> 01:09:20.668
specimens. We also performed whole exome sequencing of the ctDNA

1159
01:09:20.688 --> 01:09:21.168
samples

1160
01:09:22.728 --> 01:09:23.489
from the plasma.

1161
01:09:24.308 --> 01:09:27.998
And what we saw here is that a short course of abemaciclib, of

1162
01:09:28.088 --> 01:09:31.968
single agent abemaciclib, achieved a 31% pathologic downstaging,

1163
01:09:32.449 --> 01:09:36.148
19% pathologic complete response rate, and ctDNA

1164
01:09:36.188 --> 01:09:39.808
reduction in 69% of these evaluable

1165
01:09:39.869 --> 01:09:43.538
patients. And what we found from the RNA sequencing of the

1166
01:09:43.628 --> 01:09:47.568
matched pre and post tissues was that there was significant downregulation

1167
01:09:47.628 --> 01:09:51.348
in the expression of genes involved in homologous recombination

1168
01:09:51.369 --> 01:09:54.988
repair of double stranded breaks after DNA damage.

1169
01:09:56.308 --> 01:10:00.188
We confirmed this with imaging mass cytometry, at the protein

1170
01:10:00.248 --> 01:10:03.868
level, showing that key homologous recombination proteins,

1171
01:10:03.968 --> 01:10:07.448
including RAD51 and TOPBP1, which is a scaffold

1172
01:10:07.468 --> 01:10:10.718
protein important for RAD51 loading,

1173
01:10:10.718 --> 01:10:14.428
significantly decrease after abemaciclib, suggesting that

1174
01:10:14.468 --> 01:10:18.218
abemaciclib might impair homologous recombination in cancer cells.

1175
01:10:19.168 --> 01:10:22.828
And this led us to test whether sequential combinations of CDK4/6

1176
01:10:22.868 --> 01:10:26.428
inhibitors can be used to impair DNA damage repair, and

1177
01:10:26.488 --> 01:10:29.758
augment ADCs. And we tested this

1178
01:10:29.868 --> 01:10:33.428
in multiple urothelial cancer cell lines and patient-derived

1179
01:10:33.548 --> 01:10:36.728
organoids. And what we can see here is that sequential

1180
01:10:36.748 --> 01:10:40.628
abemaciclib enhanced the cytotoxicity of a number of

1181
01:10:40.768 --> 01:10:44.748
ADCs, including trastuzumab deruxtecan

1182
01:10:44.808 --> 01:10:48.308
or T-DXd, which has a topoisomerase inhibitor payload,

1183
01:10:48.548 --> 01:10:52.348
docetaxib vedotin, and enfirtuximab vedotin, which both

1184
01:10:52.448 --> 01:10:53.948
have MMAE payloads.

1185
01:10:55.668 --> 01:10:59.108
And we then ask, can this strategy be extended to an EV

1186
01:10:59.208 --> 01:11:02.688
resistant disease? And we developed an EV resistant

1187
01:11:02.748 --> 01:11:04.768
patient-derived organoid model using,

1188
01:11:06.108 --> 01:11:09.988
that we call WCM748. And these were exposed to

1189
01:11:10.028 --> 01:11:11.908
increasing concentrations of EV.

1190
01:11:12.408 --> 01:11:16.128
And what we ended up with, approximately 30 fold more resistant to

1191
01:11:16.188 --> 01:11:20.128
EV compared to the parental line. And if you look at the Western blot on the

1192
01:11:20.168 --> 01:11:24.128
right, you can see that these cells downregulate nectin 4, which

1193
01:11:24.168 --> 01:11:28.068
is the target of EV, but maintain RAD51 and TOPBP1,

1194
01:11:28.168 --> 01:11:29.288
and also

1195
01:11:30.328 --> 01:11:33.888
maintain or even upregulate the other

1196
01:11:34.128 --> 01:11:35.868
ADC targets such as HER2.

1197
01:11:36.788 --> 01:11:40.468
And in this EV resistant model, we again see that sequential

1198
01:11:40.508 --> 01:11:41.948
CDK4/6 inhibition

1199
01:11:42.508 --> 01:11:46.328
after the HER2 targeted

1200
01:11:46.388 --> 01:11:46.988
ADC,

1201
01:11:48.148 --> 01:11:52.028
shows significant efficacy. And this supports

1202
01:11:52.068 --> 01:11:55.308
a mechanistic rationale for testing sequential

1203
01:11:55.388 --> 01:11:59.288
CDK4/6 inhibitors with ADCs in patients who

1204
01:11:59.308 --> 01:12:00.178
progress on EV.

1205
01:12:02.008 --> 01:12:03.358
So in conclusion,

1206
01:12:04.428 --> 01:12:07.798
we think that laboratory models that recapitulate the clinical

1207
01:12:07.848 --> 01:12:11.028
resistance scenarios are critical for defining mechanisms of

1208
01:12:11.068 --> 01:12:14.788
resistance. We think that this state called deaminase

1209
01:12:14.908 --> 01:12:18.388
activated cell cycle stasis and reprogramming provides a

1210
01:12:18.928 --> 01:12:22.588
new mechanistic angle for understanding how transient

1211
01:12:22.628 --> 01:12:26.168
genotoxic stress is converted into heritable long lasting

1212
01:12:26.208 --> 01:12:26.748
effects.

1213
01:12:28.268 --> 01:12:32.108
We see that DASP establishes a heritable adaptive cell state that

1214
01:12:32.128 --> 01:12:35.768
persists across cell divisions driven by chromatin remodeling and the

1215
01:12:37.408 --> 01:12:41.068
FOXM1 SOX2 axis, and is quite distinct from other

1216
01:12:41.268 --> 01:12:44.808
